A Comparison Between Python and Rust

A Comparison Between Python and Rust

6 steps

This short tutorial provides a comparison between Python and Rust. This includes their common data types, syntax, and semantics and their ecosystems and communities.

For technical help on the StackUp platform, join our Discord to ask your question.
Join us on Discord

Helpful prior knowledge

  • Recommended to have some knowledge of Python and Rust.
  • Recommended to have an existing Python and Rust installation. Instructions can be found in the following tutorials or links:
    • https://rustup.rs
    • https://www.python.org/downloads/
    • Rust Basics > Speedrun Rust

Learning Outcomes

You will be able to:

  • Compare similarities and differences between Python and Rust.
  • Know their strengths and weaknesses based on usage and their ecosystems.
  • Learn that there are existing tools to provide integration between languages.

Tutorial Steps

Total steps: 6

  • Step 1: History and Ecosystem Maturity

    Rust, a language more recent than Python, originated as an experimental project by Graydon Hoare, a former Mozilla employee, in 2007. It was developed to address the intricate challenges associated with writing C++ code for the Firefox browser, aiming to serve as a viable alternative to C++ while mitigating its inherent complexities.

    Python is an old programming language, boasting a rich history and a vast community of developers. Its origins trace back to the late 1980s, making it significantly older than many of its contemporary counterparts in the programming landscape. However, it's in 1991 that the creator, Guido van Rossum, finally released the first version of language — Python 0.9.0.

    In the world of programming languages, the age of a language is a significant factor influencing its community adoption and the breadth of libraries and packages available, all of which contribute to the overall ecosystem surrounding the language.

    Python's popularity has resulted in a rich ecosystem around many fields in the industry, such as engineering, cloud, IoT, and data sciences. The language's longevity has fostered a large community of contributors from both open-source and industry, making it one of the most popular languages in modern history.

    Rust is still a young language. A lot of its ecosystems are a work in progress and very young such as in machine learning, game development, and peer-to-peer web technologies. Interestingly, Rust is already catching up or even considered ready in the following ecosystems:

    • Web Frameworks, Routing and Middleware
    • Asynchronous APIs and Libraries
    • Bioinformatics

    Disclaimer: Rust ecosystems are still young. Although some libraries are already production ready or used in production, it does not necessarily mean that the ecosystem as a whole is also mature. Maturity might be subjective here in some sense.

    Interest in the two languages can be represented as a graph based on data from Google Trends.

    As seen from the graph, it's pretty clear that Python is still popular and captures worldwide interest while Rust has shown a stable but increasing interest over time.

  • Step 2: Syntax and Semantics

    Although both languages do have some relationship with the C programming language, the syntax between them entirely differs.

    Python, specifically CPython, is written entirely in the C programming language. However, if we compare the syntax of the three languages, Python, C and Rust, a beginner might think that Rust must be written in C and Python is not.

    Check out the following screenshot below. All are similar programs — to print out "Hello, World!". The implementations are as follows — the first window is Rust, the second window is Python, and the last window is C.

    ℹ️ In truth, Rust is written in Rust. This is what we call "bootstrapping". We won't cover how it works but essentially, the language is written by the same language and compiled by the same tooling of that language.

    The syntax and semantics of Python is intended to welcome non-programmers without the need to learn low level concepts. It is meant to be an easy language to learn. Conversely, Rust is intended to be an alternative low level programming language to C++. So some of the syntax is carried over from C.

    Further down below is a non-exhaustive list of common semantics in different implementations. We will include C for a third comparison.

    Loops

    For Loop in Rust.

    fn main() {
	let arr = [1,2,3,4,5,6];
	for i in arr {
    	println!("{}", i);
	}
}
    Rust

    For Loop in Python.

    arr = [1,2,3,4,5,6]

for i in arr:
	print(i)
    Python

    For Loop in C.

    #include <stdio.h>

int main() {
	int arr[6] = {1,2,3,4,5,6};
	int length = sizeof(arr) / sizeof(arr[0]);
	for (size_t i = 0; i < length; i++) {
    	printf("%d\n", arr[i]);
	}
	return 0;
}
    Plain text

    Conditional Flows

    If-Statements in Rust.

    fn main() {
	let t = 10;

	if t > 4 {
    	println!("Greater than 4!");
	} else if t == 10 {
    	println!("Equals to 10!");
	} else {
    	println!("Less than 10!");
	};
}
    Rust

    If-Statements in Python.

    t = 10

if t > 4:
	print("Greater than 4!")
elif t == 10:
	print("Equals to 10!")
else:
	print("Less than 10!")
    Python

    If-Statements in C.

    #include <stdio.h>

int main(void) {
	int t = 10;

	if (t > 4) {
    	printf("%s\n", "Greater than 4!");
	} else if (t == 10) {
    	printf("%s\n", "Equals to 10!");
	} else {
    	printf("%s\n", "Less than 10!");
	}

	return 0;
}
    Plain text

    Variables

    Variables in Rust. Note that variables in Rust are immutable by default unlike the other two languages.

    fn main() {
	// Immutable by default
	let x = 10;
	// `mut` keyword allows this variable to be mutable
	let mut y = 20;
	y = y + y;
	println!("{}", y);
}
    Rust

    Variables in Python.

    x = 10
y = 20
y = y + y
print(y)
    Python

    Variables in C.

    #include <stdio.h>

int main() {
	int x = 10;
	int y = 20;
	y = y + y;
	printf("%d\n", y);
	return 0;
}
    Plain text

    This concludes this step, as this is a short tutorial, we won't go deeply into all the different ways you can write in the three languages. Do note that the syntax of a programming language also shows the intent for whom the language is for.

    For example, Rust syntax is inspired by different programming languages and programming paradigms — functional programming (such as OCaml, and Haskell), and procedural programming (such as C and C++).

    Python is mostly inspired by the ABC programming language, a language that is now defunct and rarely used. Python is also considered to be a successor of the ABC language. Even the ABC homepage links to an article of what influenced Python from its core functionality to overall syntax.

  • Step 3: Type System

    In Rust, the type system mandates rigorous definition and compile-time determinism. Employing static typing, Rust necessitates explicit type specification or compiler-driven inference for every variable, with immutability of type assignment post-initialization.

    The language's robust type system encompasses primitive types such as integers, floating-point numbers, and booleans, alongside complex types including structs, enums, and tuples. Rust's ownership and borrowing model significantly influences memory management, thereby guaranteeing safety and preempting issues like null pointer dereferencing or data races during the compilation phase.

    While Rust features type inference, its underlying static typing framework ensures type resolution early during compilation checks.

    Conversely, Python operates under dynamic typing, with type determination occurring during runtime rather than compile time. This dynamic approach facilitates greater flexibility by eliminating the need for explicit type declarations for variables.

    The Python interpreter assigns types as the program executes, which can expedite development cycles, yet introduces the potential for runtime errors if type mismatches arise. Python has types such as integers, strings, lists, dictionaries, and more intricate data structures like classes and functions.

    For example, Rust requires explicit type declarations for function parameters.

    fn add_numbers(a: i32, b: i32) -> i32 {
	a + b
}

fn main() {
	let result = add_numbers(5, 10);
	println!("The sum is: {}", result);
}
    Rust

    In contrast, Python does not require it.

    def add_numbers(a, b):
	return a + b

result = add_numbers(5, 10)
print(f"The sum is: {result}")
    Python

    Despite the introduction of type hinting in Python 3.5+ to enable optional static analysis, this feature is not enforced by the interpreter and primarily serves as documentation for developers and aids for tools such as linters or type checkers. Here is an example of the same Python code but with type hinting.

    def add_numbers(a: int, b: int):
	return a + b

result = add_numbers(5, 10)
print(f"The sum is: {result}")
    Python

    Therefore, in essence, this still does not avoid the issue of runtime errors due to mismatched types in Python.

    "compiled" and "interpreted". What are they?

    Rust is a compiled language. This means, its errors are caught during compile-time. Python is an interpreted language which means its errors are caught during runtime.

    Compile-time means your code is transformed from readable written code to machine-code, also known as compilation or code-generation. In contrast, runtime is when you are running the compiled executable or binary, or running written human-readable code inside an interpreter.

    Do note that terms compiled and interpreted are not as apparent. Python can also be considered a compiled language if you look at it closely.

    It’s not important yet to dive into this topic but if you are interested, you are free to bookmark the article Python is a Compiled Language and read it in your free time. This article explains why this distinction matters but more importantly, that programming languages should be categorised as a spectrum of properties rather than trying to put a language into one fixed category.

    In another comparison, Rust has a very extensive list of types as compared to Python. Take for example, the integer types in both languages — an int in Python handles both signed and unsigned integers. In contrast, Rust splits integer types into unsigned and signed — and each has a list of other integer types such as u8, and i64. This design decision in Rust ensures that different kinds of data can be described accurately as types.

  • Step 4: PyO3

    Rust and Python have their own advantages and disadvantages e.g. Rust aims to be a reliable and efficient language at the expense of complexity, whereas Python aims to be simple and easy to learn.

    But can we really bridge the advantages and minimise the disadvantages? There is a solution – integrating and interfacing the two languages together as necessary, allowing developers to call Rust code and bring its low-level performance to Python, or embed Python in a Rust binary — this solution is PyO3 (read as Py-oxide).

    What projects use PyO3? What even is Maturin?

    To allow integration between Python code and Rust code, PyO3 was born as an effort to bring that to reality.

    If you are a Rust developer, you can just pull the crate dependency of the project and call it a day. If you are a Python developer, you can just pull the Python library that calls the Rust code without knowing the library is just a Python wrapper.

    This is not new, some languages can already integrate with Python since Python is written in C. Most high performance scientific libraries are Python wrappers around existing C or C++ code.

    Rust is no different since it allows you to bind with C code which Python is written in.

    Example Rust crates that use PyO3 are hifitime, a very precise high fidelity time management library, and tokenizers, a tokenizer that aims to be fast for AI and ML applications.

    To easily ship Rust+Python projects that use PyO3, maturin was created for such a purpose. Not only does it help generate and develop Rust+Python projects but it also helps manage projects that use PyO3 as well as publishing projects to PyPI.

  • Step 5: Example Usage of PyO3 with maturin

    In this step, you will build a coffee machine. Well it is just a CLI tool and library that asks a user what coffee they want. The library will be written in Rust and the CLI will use the generated Python wrapper. This step was inspired from their documentation.

    We assume that you have installed the following before proceeding:

    • A working installation of Python.
    • A working installation of Rust.

    On your terminal, run the following command.

    cargo new --lib coffee_machine

    This creates a new directory called coffee_machine with the following directory and file structure.

    .
├── Cargo.toml
└── src
	└── lib.rs

2 directories, 2 files

    With your editor, open and edit your Cargo.toml file and replace all of its contents with the following code.

    [package]
name = "coffee_machine"
version = "0.1.0"
edition = "2024"

[lib]
name = "coffee_machine"
crate-type = ["cdylib"]

[dependencies]
pyo3 = { version = "0.24", features = ["abi3-py312"] }
    Plain text

    Then create a new file called pyproject.toml and write the following code to pyproject.toml.

    [build-system]
requires = ["maturin>=1.0,<2.0"]
build-backend = "maturin"

[tool.maturin]
features = ["pyo3/extension-module"]
    Plain text

    Run the following command on your terminal.

    cargo check

    This will compile the code and generate a new target directory.

    With your editor, open the lib.rs file inside the src directory. Replace the existing code with the following code.

    use pyo3::prelude::*;
use std::io;

#[pyfunction]
fn list_available_coffees() {
	println!("1. Macchiato");
	println!("2. Americano");
	println!("3. Cappuccino");
}

#[pyfunction]
fn choose_a_coffee() {
	println!("Choose a coffee:");
	loop {
    	let mut user_input = String::new();
    	io::stdin()
        	.read_line(&mut user_input)
        	.expect("Failed to read line");

    	let selected_n: u32 = match user_input.trim().parse() {
        	Ok(selection) => selection,
        	Err(_) => {
            	eprintln!("Seems you're doing something wrong. Try again.");
            	continue;
        	}
    	};

    	if selected_n == 1 {
        	println!("You have chosen Macchiato!");
        	break;
    	} else if selected_n == 2 {
        	println!("You have selected Americano!");
        	break;
    	} else if selected_n == 3 {
        	println!("You have selected Cappuccino!");
        	break;
    	} else {
        	println!("We don't have that option...");
        	break;
    	}
	}
}

#[pymodule]
fn coffee_machine(m: &Bound<'_, PyModule>) -> PyResult<()> {
	m.add_function(wrap_pyfunction!(list_available_coffees,m)?)?;
	m.add_function(wrap_pyfunction!(choose_a_coffee,m)?)?;
	Ok(())
}
    Rust

    Run the following command at the root directory of the project on your terminal.

    python3 -m venv .venv

    Then run the following command to activate your generated virtual environment. Here is one for Linux and MacOS with default shell. This also works for Git Bash for Windows too.

    source .venv/bin/activate

    For Windows with CMD.

    .\venv\Scripts\activate.bat

    For Windows With Power shell.

    .\venv\Scripts\activate.ps1

    Run the following commands.

    pip install -U pip maturin
pip freeze

    This installs the maturin executable. Run the following command to build the new Rust+Python module with maturin.

    maturin develop

    You should get a similar output like the screenshot below.

    Now you can try using the new Python module inside a Python interpreter. Run the following command to open your Python interpreter. Ensure that you are still inside the virtual environment while doing this.

    python3

    Now try to import coffee_machine inside your Python interpreter and call the functions. Check out the screenshot below for reference on how to call those functions.. The screenshot below also shows that it is working!

  • Step 6: Stacking It Up!

    Congratulations! 🎉 You have finished this tutorial. Not only did you learn more about some comparisons between Python and Rust, you also learned the basics on how to use PyO3 as well!
